</figure>
<div class="container full white">
  <h3 class="m0">Research</h3>
  <p>My research began with interviews with distributors, wine shop owners, and liquor store employees to set context and build starting domain knowledge. Later I interviewed brewery owners and consumers and conducted casual contextual inquiry with consumers, notetaking as people talked me through their wine purchasing process in retail and service environments.</p>
  <p>I also drank some wine. <em>Research!</em></p>
</div>
<div class="container mostly white mt0">
  <div class="row mt0">
    <div class="cl">
      <h5>Key Insight</h5>
      <hr class="line white">
      <h4>The Wine Supply Chain</h4>
      <p>For wine bought in stores, the chain is Producer > Distributor > Retailer > Consumer. Each have their own needs, tools, and barriers.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cl">
      <h5>Key Insight</h5>
      <hr class="line white">
      <h4>How We Buy Wine</h4>
      <p>Price. Label design. Social proof. Wine is a commodity masquerading (and sold) as a luxury good. Good wine experiences account for both the commodified portion and the emotional portion.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cl">
      <h5>Key Insight</h5>
      <hr class="line white">
      <h4>User Themes</h4>
      <p>Some consumers are solidly in the wine camp and know what they want. The rest are along a spectrum and buy wine with their own mindsets and contexts.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="container full white">
  <h3>Experience Maps</h3>
  <p>Using personas (not pictured) as swimlanes, I mapped the consumer wine experience from pre-purchase to post-consumption. The mapping process exposed gaps in my understanding of the existing consumer journey and identified opportunities for improvement.</p>
</div>
<div class="container mostly white">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="cl">
      <h5>Phase 1</h5>
      <hr class="line white"/>
      <h4>Motivation</h4>
      <p>Users are establishing need and making a plan. Ask: “why is this person hiring wine and why?”</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cl">
      <h5>Phase 2</h5>
      <hr class="line white"/>
      <h4>Acquisition</h4>
      <p>Users are finding, evaluating, and purchasing wine. This phase is the “how?” phase.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cl">
      <h5>Phase 3</h5>
      <hr class="line white"/>
      <h4>Consumption</h4>
      <p>Users are delivering, serving, and drinking wine, all in different ways.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cl">
      <h5>Phase 4</h5>
      <hr class="line white"/>
      <h4>Reflection</h4>
      <p>Users are internalizing their experience with the wine based on taste, expectations, and appropriateness.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="container full white pt4">
  <h3>Hypotheses & Prototyping</h3>
  <p class="m0">The prototyping process is a series of experiments in which the designer uses artifacts to elicit new information and test key elements of a proposed solution. I built two prototypes and both elicited insights about the industry and user experience while validating and invalidating core value propositions.</p>
